{"parentUuid":"7554eac0-876e-4d6e-b21e-1648154aaec6","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"a744b966-e97b-4820-8175-d45d9de27812","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"ai-erdos-7","agentId":"a0b4fda0a514f295e","slug":"virtual-plotting-ullman","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HSuTohnwsL3CZrb2HPJe2F","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright 2026 The Formal Conjectures Authors.\n     3→\n     4→Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n     5→you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n     6→You may obtain a copy of the License at\n     7→\n     8→    https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n     9→\n    10→Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n    11→distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n    12→WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n    13→See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n    14→limitations under the License.\n    15→-/\n    16→\n    17→import FormalConjectures.Util.ProblemImports\n    18→\n    19→/-!\n    20→# Erdős Problem 15\n    21→\n    22→*Reference:* [erdosproblems.com/15](https://www.erdosproblems.com/15)\n    23→\n    24→Is the alternating series $\\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} (-1)^n \\cdot n / p_n$ convergent, where $p_n$\n    25→denotes the $n$-th prime? Tao has proved convergence assuming a strong form of the\n    26→Hardy–Littlewood prime tuples conjecture.\n    27→-/\n    28→\n    29→open Filter\n    30→\n    31→open scoped BigOperators Topology\n    32→\n    33→namespace Erdos15\n    34→\n    35→/--\n    36→Is it true that the alternating series\n    37→$$\\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} (-1)^n \\cdot \\frac{n}{p_n}$$\n    38→converges, where $p_n$ denotes the $n$-th prime?\n    39→\n    40→This is an open problem. Tao has proved convergence assuming a strong form\n    41→of the Hardy–Littlewood prime tuples conjecture.\n    42→\n    43→We state convergence as: the sequence of partial sums\n    44→$$S_N = \\sum_{n=1}^{N} (-1)^n \\cdot \\frac{n}{p_n}$$\n    45→converges to a real limit $L$.\n    46→\n    47→Using 0-indexed `Nat.nth Nat.Prime`, the $n$-th term ($n : \\mathbb{N}$, 0-indexed) is\n    48→$(-1)^{n+1} \\cdot (n+1) / p_{n+1}$,\n    49→which corresponds to the 1-indexed term $(-1)^{n+1} \\cdot (n+1)/p_{n+1}$.\n    50→-/\n    51→@[category research open, AMS 11 40]\n    52→theorem erdos_15 : answer(sorry) ↔ ∃ L : ℝ,\n    53→    Tendsto\n    54→      (fun N : ℕ => ∑ n ∈ Finset.range N,\n    55→        (-1 : ℝ) ^ (n + 1) * ((n + 1 : ℝ) / (Nat.nth Nat.Prime n : ℝ)))\n    56→      atTop (nhds L) := by\n    57→  sorry\n    58→\n    59→end Erdos15\n    60→"}]},"uuid":"61c13856-e8ce-4138-8386-3b74a9b4a1d8","timestamp":"2026-03-09T19:37:47.583Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"7554eac0-876e-4d6e-b21e-1648154aaec6"}
